===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|coppe|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} *{{term||coppe|lang=ang}}, as in {{term|atorcoppe|ātorcoppe|spider|lit=venom head|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|copp||top, summit, head|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|kuppaz|vault, round vessel, head|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|gū-|to bend, curve|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|koppe|lang=dum}}, {{term|kobbe||spider|lang=dum}}. More at {{l|en|cobweb}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} A [[spider]].

===Etymology 2===
Possibly from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|capere||to capture|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|capio|capere|lang=la|to seize, to grasp}}; or possibly from {{etyl|nl}} {{term|kapen||to steal|lang=nl}}, from {{etyl|fy}} {{term|kapia|kāpia|to take away}}, from {{etyl|ofs}} {{term|kapia}}, to buy.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|cop|p|ing}}

# {{transitive|formerly|_|dialect|now|_|informal}} to [[obtain]], to purchase (as in drugs), to get hold of, to [[take]]
#* '''2005,''' Martin Torgoff, ''Can't Find My Way Home'', Simon &amp; Schuster, page 10,
#*: Heroin appeared on the streets of our town for the first time, and Innie watched helplessly as his sixteen-year-old brother began taking the train to Harlem to '''cop''' smack.
# {{transitive}} to (be forced to) [[take]]; to [[receive]]; to [[shoulder]]; to [[bear]]
#: When caught, he would often '''cop''' a vicious blow from his father
# {{transitive}} to [[steal]]
# {{transitive}} to [[adopt]]
#: ''No need to '''cop''' an attitude with me, junior.''
# {{intransitive|usually with "to"}} to [[admit]]
#: ''Harold '''copped''' to being known as "Dirty Harry".''
#* {{quote-book|title=Mr. Paradise|page=295|author=Elmore Leonard|year=2005|passage=He shot a guy in a bar on Martin Luther King Day and '''copped''' to first-degree manslaughter}}

